=== Ch5_Intro ===
Chapter 5: Supporting families. # diagram: supporting_families.jpg

Three questions about parental controls. Short chapter, big implications.

*   [Show me.]
    -> Ch5_Q60

=== Ch5_Q60 ===
Question 60 asks:

"To what extent do you agree or disagree: Parents should have control over the online experiences of their children."

Strongly agree to Strongly disagree.

*   [Who would disagree with that?]
    -> Ch5_Q60_Analysis

=== Ch5_Q60_Analysis ===
Almost nobody. And that's the point.

The question is framed as "control" not "support." There's a world of difference between empowering parents with tools and information, versus mandating state-mediated surveillance infrastructure.

"Parents should be able to set boundaries" — almost everyone agrees.

"The state should mandate and enforce technological systems that give parents control" — very different proposition.

A near-universal "strongly agree" here will be cited as public support for whatever parental control mandates follow. The devil is in the implementation, not the principle.

*   [What about Q61?]
    -> Ch5_Q61

=== Ch5_Q61 ===
Question 61 asks:

"How should this level of control change for children of different ages? For example, a 16-year-old and an 11-year-old."

This is a free-text box—and it's actually a good question. The answer obviously depends on the child, the family, and the context.

Which is exactly why government-mandated, one-size-fits-all restrictions are the wrong tool. On-device parental controls already let parents adjust settings per child, per age, per app. No government infrastructure required.

*   [What about Q62?]
    -> Ch5_Q62

=== Ch5_Q62 ===
Question 62 asks:

"What would help parents and carers to more effectively use parental controls?"

Options include: more information on purchase, help from platforms on setup, greater standardisation across tools.

*   [What should I think about?]
    -> Ch5_Q62_Analysis

=== Ch5_Q62_Analysis ===
This is the question where the "Better Parental Controls" story is directly relevant.

The tools already exist. Apple Screen Time, Google Family Link, built-in router controls. The problem isn't that the tools don't exist—it's that parents don't know about them, or find them confusing.

The solution is education and better UX—not new surveillance infrastructure.

If you've used parental controls and found them effective, say so. If you've found them confusing, say what would help. Either way, this is your chance to make the case that on-device, family-level controls are the right approach—not government-mandated, platform-level age verification.

This is the last chapter. And it's the most important thing to say throughout the entire consultation: on-device parental controls and education work. They respect family autonomy. They don't require surveillance. They can't be bypassed by going to a different website.

If you believe this, say it here. And say it in every other free-text box you've encountered.

